LEARNING GOALS:¶

1) Calculate the autocorrelation at a range of lags using two methods available in python (np.correlate, dot products) 2) Estimate the effective sample size (N) using the lag-1 autocorrelation 3) Evaluate the influence of changing the sampling frequency and the specified weather variable on the memory/redness of the data as quantified by the autocorrelation and N.

DATA and UNDERLYING SCIENCE MOTIVATION:¶

In this notebook, you will analyze the memory (red noise) in weather observations from Fort Colins, Colorado at Christman Field. The observations are from one year, but are sampled hourly. The default settings for the notebook analyze the air temperature in degrees F sampled once daily (every midnight). But other standard weather variables and sampling frequencies can also be easily analyzed. The file containing the data is called christman_2016.csv and it is a comma-delimited text file.

#Find the lag-one autocorrelation (AR1)
tseries=X_daily
sigma=np.std(tseries)  ## calculate the standard deviation
mean=np.mean(tseries)  ## calculate the mean
n=len(tseries)         ## calculate the length of the timeseries
lag=20                  ## warning: you cannot change this to be a negative lag. 
                       ## this cell does not work for negative lags - Can you see why?

## remove the mean
tseries1=tseries-mean

##Create two timeseries of the data at t=t1 and t=t2
t1_m=tseries1.iloc[0:-1*lag] #negative lag will break the indexing, since the other one should be moved fwd instead
t2_m=tseries1.iloc[lag:]
#print(t1_m.shape)
#print(t2_m.shape)

#Method #1
#Calculate the autocorrelation using numpy correlate lagN
lagNauto_np=np.correlate(t1_m,t2_m,mode='valid')/(n-lag)/(sigma**2)
print('lag',lag,'autocorrelation np.correlate:',round(lagNauto_np[0],3))

#Method #2 - direct calculation
#Calculate the autocorrelation using numpy dot
## (https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy-1.13.0/reference/generated/numpy.dot.html)
lagNauto=np.dot(t1_m,t2_m)/(n-lag)/sigma**2 ## Barnes Chapter 2 Eq. 68 divided by the variance
print('lag',lag,'autocorrelation direct calc:',round(lagNauto,3))

if lag==1: alpha=lagNauto

lag 20 autocorrelation np.correlate: 0.616
lag 20 autocorrelation direct calc: 0.616

The manual autocorrelation doesn't work for negative lags because of how the indexing is set up. A more general (but less explicit) manual autocorrelation can be done using DataFrame.shift()

#Find the lag-one autocorrelation (AR1)
tseries=X_daily
sigma=np.std(tseries)  ## calculate the standard deviation
mean=np.mean(tseries)  ## calculate the mean
n=len(tseries)         ## calculate the length of the timeseries
lag=-350                 ## warning: you cannot change this to be a negative lag. 
                       ## this cell does not work for negative lags - Can you see why?

## remove the mean
tseries1=tseries-mean

##Create two timeseries of the data at t=t1 and t=t2
 #shift the timeseries either forward or backward (out-of bounds indexes get replaced with NaNs)
t1_m=tseries1
t2_m=tseries1.shift(-lag) #positive lag = negative shift
trunc_mask = t2_m.notna() #identify where the shifted timeseries has missing values
t1_m, t2_m=t1_m[trunc_mask],t2_m[trunc_mask] #remove these values from both series
print(t1_m.shape)
print(t2_m.shape)

#Method #1
#Calculate the autocorrelation using numpy correlate lagN
lagNauto_np=np.correlate(t1_m,t2_m,mode='valid')/(n-np.abs(lag))/(sigma**2)
print('lag',lag,'autocorrelation np.correlate:',round(lagNauto_np[0],3))

#Method #2 - direct calculation
#Calculate the autocorrelation using numpy dot
## (https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy-1.13.0/reference/generated/numpy.dot.html)
lagNauto=np.dot(t1_m,t2_m)/(n-np.abs(lag))/sigma**2 ## Barnes Chapter 2 Eq. 68 divided by the variance
print('lag',lag,'autocorrelation direct calc:',round(lagNauto,3))

if lag==1: alpha=lagNauto

#print(len(lags))
#print(len(np.correlate(tseries1,tseries1,mode='same')))
autocorrelation_function=np.correlate(tseries1,tseries1,mode='same')/((n-np.abs(lags))*sigma**2)  ##Eq. 67 divided by variance
plt.plot(range(-1*half,half),autocorrelation_function)
plt.xlim([-40,40]);
plt.ylim([0.0,1.0]);

plt.ylabel('Autocorrelation',fontsize=14);

It should be symmetric about zero, since the covariance is commutable, i.e. $$ \overline{x^\prime y^\prime} = \overline{y^\prime x^\prime}. $$ Note $$ \overline{x(t-\tau)^\prime x(t)^\prime} = \overline{x(t)^\prime x(t+\tau)^\prime}, $$ since the starting point of $t$ is irrelevant. Using the commutability of the covariance, then $$ \overline{x(t-\tau)^\prime x(t)^\prime} = \overline{x(t+\tau)^\prime x(t)^\prime}, $$ therefore, the autocovariance is symmetric about zero.

Memory in AR1 is (Barnes Eq. 72) $$ a = \rho(\Delta t) = \frac{\gamma(\Delta t)}{\gamma(0)},$$ which is calculated below:

both the mean and the standard deviation fall precipitously when the lag approaches the length of the data record. It kind of makes sense why the autocorrelation would be $>1$, since the $\sigma$ and $\bar{x}$ aren't correct for the sample any longer? Note this happens because as the record shortens we are removing seasonal, and then synoptic variability.

In [92]:
#Find the lag-one autocorrelation (AR1)
tseries=X_daily
sigma=np.std(tseries)  ## calculate the standard deviation
mean=np.mean(tseries)  ## calculate the mean
n=len(tseries)         ## calculate the length of the timeseries
lag=-350                 ## warning: you cannot change this to be a negative lag. 
                       ## this cell does not work for negative lags - Can you see why?


lags_full=np.arange(-n+1,n);
rhos = [ ]
for lag in lags_full:
    tseries1 = tseries - tseries.shift(-lag).dropna().mean() #adaptive mean
    t1_m=tseries1
    t2_m=tseries1.shift(-lag) #positive lag = negative shift
    
    trunc_mask = t2_m.notna() #identify where the shifted timeseries has missing values
    t1_m, t2_m=t1_m[trunc_mask],t2_m[trunc_mask] #remove these values from both series
    
    lagNauto=np.dot(t1_m,t2_m)/(n-np.abs(lag))/sigma**2 ## Barnes Chapter 2 Eq. 68 divided by the variance
    rhos.append(lagNauto)
    
plt.plot(lags_full,rhos,label='using lag-shortened mean')
plt.plot(lags_full,foo,label='using overall mean')
plt.xlabel('lag (days)')
plt.ylabel('autocorrelation')
plt.title('autocorrelation using lag-shortened means vs not')
plt.legend()

nice! So perhaps the covariance requires that we subtract the mean of the actual data used, rather than the population. I suppose the standard deviation trick didn't work because it's actually the lag-0 autocorrelation, which by default includes the whole dataset. Anyways, this looks reasonable to me (it fixed the problem of $\rho(\tau)>1$), but I'm not totally sure if it's "right" :)

In [113]:
# TINKERING
# redo code for each variable in the dataFrame except for 'day' and 'hour'
# use the tweaked autocorrelation that works for long lag times
# pseudocode:
#   1. declare a subplot for each data variable
#   2. iterate over subplots, data variables
#   3. preprocess (select every day's midnight value)
#   4. calculate autocorrelation at lags from -365 to 365
#   5. show on subplot

fig,axes = plt.subplots(2,5,sharex=True,sharey=True,figsize=(15,7),dpi=150)
axes_flat = axes.flatten()

X=data['wind_dir']
X_daily=X[::24]
tseries=X_daily
sigma=np.std(tseries)  ## calculate the standard deviation
mean=np.mean(tseries)  ## calculate the mean
n=len(tseries)         ## calculate the length of the timeseries
lag=-350                 ## warning: you cannot change this to be a negative lag. 
                       ## this cell does not work for negative lags - Can you see why?

lags_full=np.arange(-n+1,n)
keep_vars = set(data.columns) - set(['day','hour']) #skip coords
for ax,name in zip(axes_flat,keep_vars):
    rhos = [ ]
    X=data[name]
    X_daily=X[::24]
    tseries=X_daily
    sigma=np.std(tseries)  ## calculate the standard deviation
    mean=np.mean(tseries)  ## calculate the mean
    n=len(tseries)         ## calculate the length of the timeseries
    for lag in lags_full:
        tseries1 = tseries - tseries.shift(-lag).dropna().mean() #adaptive mean
        t1_m=tseries1
        t2_m=tseries1.shift(-lag) #positive lag = negative shift

        trunc_mask = t2_m.notna() #identify where the shifted timeseries has newly-missing values
        t1_m, t2_m=t1_m[trunc_mask],t2_m[trunc_mask] #remove these values from both series

        lagNauto=np.dot(t1_m,t2_m)/(n-np.abs(lag))/sigma**2 ## Barnes Chapter 2 Eq. 68 divided by the variance
        rhos.append(lagNauto) #append to list of autocorrelations at lags
    ax.plot(lags_full,rhos)
    ax.set_title(name)
    if ax in axes[-1,:]: ax.set_xlabel('lag (days)')
    if ax in axes[:,0]: ax.set_ylabel('autocorrelation')

axes_flat[0].set_xlim(-180,180)
fig.tight_layout()

I think seeing the different patterns side-by-side is pretty neat! I think they highlight different frequencies of variability:

  • temp_F and dewtemp_F: smoothly varying, dominated by seasonal change
  • pres_Hg and windgust_dir: regularly-spaced spikes perhaps indicate autocorrelation with synoptic-scale weather events, frontal passages etc.
  • wind_mph, wind_dir, windgust, and SOLIN_Wm2: not much going on here, which is true for the SOLIN variable because I left the sampling at midnight
  • RH: looks like a mix of the synoptically-driven spikes like pressure and the long-term correlation in temperature. Probably because there's a bit of a wet and dry season? But it's also very weak so it might just be nothing.
  • Prec_inches: I think this one's bogus because it's almost a binary variable; the spikes (maybe) just correspond to precip events

Of course, I should "look at my data" before jumping to conclusions. Let's spot-check pressure:
